<section xml:id="C24.S12">
<title>Zeros</title>        
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S12.SS1">
<title>Bernoulli Polynomials: Real Zeros</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.s1">
In the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m1">0\leq x\leq 1</Math> the only zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m2">B_{2n+1}\left(x\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m3">n=1,2,\ldots</Math> , are <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m4">0,\tfrac{1}{2},1</Math> , and the only zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m5">B_{2n}\left(x\right)-B_{2n}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m6">n=1,2,\ldots</Math> , are <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p1.m7">0,1</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.s1">
For the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m1">\tfrac{1}{2}\leq x&lt;\infty</Math> denote the zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m2">B_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m3">x_{j}^{(n)}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m4">j=1,2,\ldots</Math> , with <Math equation-number="24.12.1" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E1">\tfrac{1}{2}\leq x_{1}^{(n)}\leq x_{2}^{(n)}\leq\cdots</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.s2">
Then the zeros in the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m5">-\infty&lt;x\leq\frac{1}{2}</Math> are <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p2.m6">1-x_{j}^{(n)}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p3.s1">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p3.m1">n(\geq 2)</Math> is even <Math equation-number="24.12.2" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E2">\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{2^{n+2}\pi}&lt;x^{(n)}_{1}&lt;\frac{3}{4}+\frac{1}{2^{n+1}\pi},</Math> , <Math equation-number="24.12.3" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E3">x^{(n)}_{1}-\frac{3}{4}\sim\frac{1}{2^{n+1}\pi}, if n\to\infty,</Math> and as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p3.m2">n\to\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p3.m3">m(\geq 1)</Math> fixed, <Math equation-number="24.12.4" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E4">x^{(n)}_{2m-1}\to m-\tfrac{1}{4},x^{(n)}_{2m}\to m+\tfrac{1}{4}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.s1">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m1">n</Math> is odd <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m2">x^{(n)}_{1}=\frac{1}{2}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m3">x^{(n)}_{2}=1</Math> <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m4">(n\geq 3)</Math> , and as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m5">n\to\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p4.m6">m(\geq 1)</Math> fixed, <Math equation-number="24.12.5" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E5">x^{(n)}_{2m-1}\to m-\tfrac{1}{2},x^{(n)}_{2m}\to m</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.s1">
Let <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.m1">R(n)</Math> be the total number of real zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.m2">B_{n}\left(x\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.s2">
Then <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.m3">R(n)=n</Math> when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS1.p5.m4">1\leq n\leq 5</Math> , and <Math equation-number="24.12.6" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E6">R(n)\sim 2n/(\pi e), if n\to\infty</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S12.SS2">
<title>Euler Polynomials: Real Zeros</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.s1">
For the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m1">\frac{1}{2}\leq x&lt;\infty</Math> denote the zeros of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m2">E_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m3">y^{(n)}_{j}</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m4">j=1,2,\ldots</Math> , with <Math equation-number="24.12.7" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E7">\tfrac{1}{2}\leq y^{(n)}_{1}\leq y^{(n)}_{2}\leq\cdots</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.s2">
Then the zeros in the interval <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m5">-\infty&lt;x\leq\frac{1}{2}</Math> are <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p1.m6">1-y^{(n)}_{j}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2.s1">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2.m1">n(\geq 2)</Math> is even <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2.m2">y^{(n)}_{1}=1</Math> , and as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2.m3">n\to\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p2.m4">m(\geq 1)</Math> fixed, <Math equation-number="24.12.8" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E8">y^{(n)}_{m}\to m</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3.s1">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3.m1">n</Math> is odd <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3.m2">y^{(n)}_{1}=\tfrac{1}{2}</Math> , <Math equation-number="24.12.9" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E9">\frac{3}{2}-\frac{\pi^{n+1}}{3(n!)}&lt;y^{(n)}_{2}&lt;\frac{3}{2}, if n=3,7,11,\dots,</Math> <Math equation-number="24.12.10" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E10">\frac{3}{2}&lt;y^{(n)}_{2}&lt;\frac{3}{2}+\frac{\pi^{n+1}}{3(n!)}, if n=5,9,13,\dots,</Math> and as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3.m3">n\to\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS2.p3.m4">m(\geq 1)</Math> fixed, <Math equation-number="24.12.11" mode="display" xml:id="C24.S12.E11">y^{(n)}_{2m}\to m-\tfrac{1}{2}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S12.SS3">
<title>Complex Zeros</title>        
   
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C24.S12.SS3.p1.s1">
For complex zeros of Bernoulli and Euler polynomials, seeDelange (1987) and Dilcher (1988).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C24.S12.SS3.p1.s2">
A related topic is the irreducibility of Bernoulli and Euler polynomials.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C24.S12.SS3.p1.s3">
For details and references, see Dilcher (1987b), Kimura (1988), orAdelberg (1992).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C24.S12.SS4">
<title>Multiple Zeros</title>           
<para xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.s1">
 <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.m1">B_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.m2">n=1,2,\ldots</Math> , has no multiple zeros.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.s2">
The only polynomial <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.m3">E_{n}\left(x\right)</Math> with multiple zeros is <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C24.S12.SS4.p1.m4">E_{5}\left(x\right)=(x-\frac{1}{2})(x^{2}-x-1)^{2}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>

 
</subsection>
 
</section>
